At 4 p.m. on the 22nd we weighed anchor passed out of the harbour. As we drew out a Greek ship, carrying the reservists of that country, passed us. She appeared to be heavily loaded, the men being in the highest spirit at their chance of war with Bulgaria.
That night many of the usual precautions were taken against submarines, which according to reports (not rumours) are plentiful in these waters. Smoking was prohibited, all lights were of course put out, guards sentries armed loaded with ball set at every point of vantage on the ship.
